The PC Engine version was well received by critics.<ref name="WFTPCEp-47">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/bi-weekly-famitsu-no.-71-march-31st-1989/Bi-Weekly%20Famitsu%20-%20No.%2071%20March%2031st%2C%201989%20%28Compressed%29#page/n13/mode/1up|title=NEW GAMES CROSS REVIEW: P-47 (PCエンジン)|magazine=[[Famitsu]]|issue=71|publisher=[[ASCII Corporation]]|date=March 31, 1989|page=14|language=ja}}</ref><ref name="MPCEp-47">{{cite magazine|title=P-47|magazine={{ill|マル勝PCエンジン|lt=Marukatsu PC Engine|ja|Marukatsu PC Engine}}|publisher=[[Kadokawa Shoten]]|date=1989|lang=ja}}</ref> ''Computer and Video Games''{{'}} Paul Glancey praised the PC Engine port for its graphics as well as sound and gameplay, regarding it to be a "very tough arcade conversion, but veterans of computer wars past should find ''P-47''{{'}}s good blasting action both addictive and challenging."<ref name="CVGPCEp-47">{{cite magazine|last=Glancey|first=Paul|url=https://archive.org/stream/cvg-magazine-092/CVG_092_Jun_1989#page/n93/mode/1up|title=Mean Machines: P-47 (PC Engine)|magazine=[[Computer and Video Games]]|issue=92|publisher=[[EMAP]]|date=June 1989|page=94}}</ref> ''The Games Machine''{{'}}s Phil Harrison commended the PC Engine port for its arcade-accurate presentation and music.<ref name="TGMPCEp-47">{{cite magazine|last=Harrison|first=Phil|url=https://archive.org/stream/the-games-machine-19/TheGamesMachine19#page/n21/mode/1up|title=Consoles - PC Engine: P-47|magazine=[[The Games Machine]]|issue=19|publisher=[[Newsfield Publications]]|date=June 1989|page=22|access-date=2020-10-15|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010172952/http://archive.org/stream/the-games-machine-19/TheGamesMachine19#page/n21/mode/1up|archive-date=2016-10-10|url-status=live}}</ref> Readers of the Japanese ''[[PC Engine Fan]]'' magazine voted to give the PC Engine port a 20.69 out of 30 score, ranking at the number 287 spot.<ref name="PCEFp-47">{{cite magazine|title=PC Engine All Catalog '93 10月号特別付録 - P-47|magazine=[[PC Engine Fan]]|volume=6|issue=10|publisher=[[Tokuma Shoten]]|date=1 October 1993|page=91|lang=ja}}</ref>

The Amiga port received mixed reviews from critics.<ref name="AMAGAp-47"/> ''[[CU Amiga-64]]''{{'}}s Mike Pattenden criticized the sound and difficulty level of the Amiga port.<ref name="CUAmiga-64AGAp-47"/> ''[[Amiga Format]]''{{'}}s Andy Smith praised the Amiga port for its arcade-accurate presentation and co-op play.<ref name="AFAGAp-47"/> Max Magenauer of German magazine ''Amiga Joker'' gave the Amiga port a mixed outlook, criticizing the graphics as well as sound, controls and gameplay.<ref name="AJAGAp-47"/> When reviewing the Amiga port, ''[[Amiga Action]]''{{'}}s Steve McNally as well as Italian magazine ''Amiga Byte'' drew comparisons with ''Silkworm''.<ref name="AAAGAp-47"/><ref name="ABAGAp-47">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/AmigaByte21#page/n25/mode/1up|title=Software Express - P-47 Thunderbolt|magazine=Amiga Byte|issue=21|publisher=Elettronica 2000|date=April 1990|page=26|lang=it}}</ref> ''[[Zzap!64]]''{{'}}s Stuart Wynne and Phil King commended the Amiga port for its presentation, visuals, sound and co-op feature but noted the retail price to be high for a conversion.<ref name="Z!64AGAC64p-47"/> French magazine ''[[Joystick (magazine)|Joystick]]'' and ''[[Tilt (French magazine)|Tilt]]''{{'}}s Alain Huyghues-Lacour regarded the Amiga port to be superior than the Atari ST version, praising the visuals and playability.<ref name="JstickAGAp-47"/><ref name="TiltCPCSTp-47"/> Daniel Melin of Swedish magazine ''Datormagazin'' praised the visuals but criticized other areas of the Amiga port.<ref name="DatorAGAp-47"/> ''[[Amiga User International]]''{{'}}s Tony Horgan criticized the presentation, graphics, design, sound and gameplay of the Amiga port.<ref name="AUIAGAp-47"/>

As with the Amiga version, the Atari ST iteration was met with mixed reception. ''[[Computer and Video Games]]''{{'}}s Paul Rand regarded the ST port of ''P-47'' to be a playable title as well as a good arcade conversion, but noted the graphics to be "very garish."<ref name="CVGSTp-47"/> ''[[The One (magazine)|The One]]''{{'}}s Brian Nesbitt remarked that the visuals in the ST port were colorful but unremarkable while criticizing other issues, stating that "''P-47''{{'}}s fun in a mindless sort of way, and it's tough enough to keep most players on their toes - but not for any great length of time... especially at the price."<ref name="TOSTp-47"/> ''[[ST Action]]'' praised its appealing simplicity and playability.<ref name="STASTp-47"/> As with the Amiga iteration, French magazine ''Génération 4'' as well as ''Micro News''{{'}}s Marc Lacombe and ''[[Zero (video game magazine)|Zero]]''{{'}}s [[Matt Bielby]] drew comparisons with ''Silkworm'' when reviewing the ST port.<ref name="G4STp-47"/><ref name="MNSTp-47"/><ref name="ZSTp-47"/> ''[[Aktueller Software Markt]]''{{'}}s Peter Braun praised the graphics, sound and gameplay of the ST port, stating that "''P 47'' can be recommended to all those who are fed up with adventure and strategy construction sites and want to hit the wall again with a good action game."<ref name="ASMSTp-47"/> Martin Gaksch of German magazine ''Power Play'' commended the gameplay speed and co-op feature of the ST port but criticized various in-game issues, regarding the game to be an average shooting game.<ref name="PPSTp-47"/> ''Joystick''{{'}}s Jean-Marc Demoly commended the ST port for its realistic-looking graphics, parallax scrolling effects, sound design and playability.<ref name="JstickCPCSTp-47"/> ''Tilt''{{'}}s Alain Huyghues-Lacour commended the visuals and animations, recommending arcade arcade players enough to give the ST port a try.<ref name="TiltCPCSTp-47"/>

French magazine ''Amstar'' praised the Amstrad CPC port for being "an excellent conversion of the arcade game of the same name", praising the visual presentation and difficulty level.<ref name="AmstarCPCp-47">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/AMSTAR/AMSTAR_43#page/n59/mode/2up|title=Banc D'essai Logiciels - P-47 (Arcade)|magazine={{ill|Amstar (magazine)|lt=Amstar|fr|Amstar (magazine de jeu vidéo)}}|issue=43|publisher=Soracom Editions|date=March 1990|pages=60–61|lang=fr}}</ref> ''[[Amstrad Action]]''{{'}}s Trenton Webb and Rod Lawton praised the CPC port for its visual presentation and addictive gameplay, though Lawton ultimately remarked that the game was "just another shoot-em-up when all's said and done".<ref name="AACPCp-47">{{cite magazine|last1=Webb|first1=Trenton|last2=Lawton|first2=Rod|url=https://archive.org/stream/amstrad-action-054#page/n41/mode/2up|title=Action Test - P-47 Thunderbolt (Firebird)|magazine=[[Amstrad Action]]|issue=54|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=March 1990|pages=42–43}}</ref> Alian of French publication ''Amstrad Cent Pour Cent'' commended the overall quality of the CPC port.<ref name="ACPCp-47">{{cite magazine|author=Alian|url=https://archive.org/stream/AMSTRAD_CENTPOURCENT/AMSTRAD_CENT_POUR_CENT_24#page/n43/mode/1up|title=P-47|magazine={{ill|Amstrad Cent Pour Cent|lt=Amstrad Cent Pour Cent|fr|Amstrad Cent pour cent}}|issue=24|publisher={{ill|Média Système Édition|lt=Média Système Édition|fr|Média Système Édition}}|date=March 1990|page=89|lang=fr}}</ref> ''Joystick''{{'}}s Bó TGV drew comparison with ''Silkworm'' when reviewing the CPC port but commended the conversion for its presentation and sound.<ref name="JstickCPCSTp-47"/> ''Tilt''{{'}}s Alain Huyghues-Lacour praised the CPC port for being better than the Atari ST iteration, commending the graphics and gameplay but lamented the lack of co-op play.<ref name="TiltCPCSTp-47"/>

''Zzap!64''{{'}}s Stuart Wynne and Phil King regarded the Commodore 64 port to be not as slick as the Amiga iteration, criticizing the lack of co-op play as well as the visual presentation.<ref name="Z!64AGAC64p-47"/> ''Aktueller Software Markt''{{'}}s Torsten Blum regarded the C64 port to be disappointing, criticizing the jerky-scrolling background graphics and lack of music during gameplay, however the sprite animations were praised.<ref name="ASMC64p-47">{{cite magazine|last=Blum|first=Torsten|url=https://archive.org/stream/Aktueller_Software_Markt_-_Ausgabe_1990.05#page/n49/mode/1up|title=Konvertierungen - P47 Thunderbolt (C-64)|magazine=[[Aktueller Software Markt]]|issue=42|publisher=Tronic Verlag|date=May 1990|page=67|lang=de}}</ref> ''[[Your Commodore]]''{{'}}s Ashley Cotter-Cairns gave the C64 port an overall negative outlook, criticizing the sprite flickering indistinct backgrounds, among other issues.<ref name="YCC64p-47">{{cite magazine|last=Cotter-Cairns|first=Ashley|url=https://archive.org/stream/68-your-commodore-magazine#page/n25/mode/1up|title=Game Reviews: P47 Thunderbolt (Firebird)|magazine=[[Your Commodore]]|issue=68|publisher=[[Argus Specialist Publications]]|date=May 1990|page=26}}</ref> ''[[Commodore Force]]''{{'}}s Miles Guttery criticized the preset enemy patterns but regarded the C64 port to be a "fair trigger exercise."<ref name="CForceC64p-47">{{cite magazine|last=Guttery|first=Miles|url=https://archive.org/details/zzap64-magazine-098/page/n16/mode/1up|title=Round-Up! - Slots Of Fun! Part Two: P-47 Thunderbolt (Firebird)|magazine=[[Commodore Force]]|issue=8|publisher=[[Europress Impact]]|date=August 1993|page=17}}</ref> ''The Games Machine''{{'}}s Warren Lapworth praised the MS-DOS port for its arcade-accurate visuals and adjustable gameplay options but criticized the sound effects and keyboard controls, stating that "P47's still a jolly little shoot-'em-up."<ref name="TGMDOSp-47">{{cite magazine|last=Lapworth|first=Warren|url=https://archive.org/stream/the-games-machine-34/TheGamesMachine34#page/n55/mode/1up|title=Reviews - Shorts: P47 Thunderbolt (Firebird/IBM PC)|magazine=[[The Games Machine]]|issue=34|publisher=[[Newsfield Publications]]|date=September 1990|page=56}}</ref>

''Crash''{{'}}s Mark Caswell and Nick Roberts commended the ZX Spectrum port for its visual presentation, however Caswell stated that "''P-47'' holds nothing new in the way it plays, but could just give the hardened shoot-'em-up fan a challenge."<ref name="CrashZXSp-47">{{cite magazine|last1=Caswell|first1=Mark|last2=Roberts|first2=Nick|url=https://archive.org/stream/crash-magazine-74/Crash_74_Mar_1990#page/n43/mode/1up|title=Reviews - P47 Thunderbolt|magazine=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]|issue=74|publisher=[[Newsfield Publications]]|date=March 1990|page=44}}</ref> ''[[Sinclair User]]''{{'}}s Jim Douglas drew comparison with ''Silkworm'' but commended the visuals and playability, stating that the Spectrum port is a "clean conversion of an average coin-op. Low on skill but high on kill."<ref name="SUZXSp-47">{{cite magazine|last=Douglas|first=Jim|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-096/SinclairUser_096_Mar_1990#page/n34/mode/1up|title=Games Review: P47|magazine=[[Sinclair User]]|issue=96|publisher=[[EMAP]]|date=March 1990|pages=36–37}}</ref> ''Your Sinclair''{{'}}s Robin Candy regarded the Spectrum port to be a traditional horizonal-scrolling shoot 'em up, criticizing the overly detailed backgrounds that leads enemy bullets blend within the scenery, however Candy stated that "''P47'' may not be ''[[R-Type]]'', but it's a perfectly competent and satisfying addition to the Speccy stable of shoot-'em-ups."<ref name="YSZXSp-47">{{cite magazine|last=Candy|first=Robin|url=https://archive.org/stream/Your_Sinclair_052#page/31/mode/1up|title=Reviews - P47|magazine=[[Your Sinclair]]|issue=52|publisher=[[Future Publishing]]|date=April 1990|page=31}}</ref> Spanish magazine ''MicroHobby'' praised the Spectrum port for its visuals, controls, sound and replayability.<ref name="MHZXSp-47">{{cite magazine|url=https://archive.org/stream/microhobby-magazine-203.pdf#page/n31/mode/1up|title=Nuevo: P47 Thunderbolt - Como en los mejores tiempos del frenético arcade vertical, Firebird nos sitúa de nuevo a los mandos de un rapidísimo avión depredador|magazine={{ill|MicroHobby|lt=MicroHobby|es|MicroHobby}}|volume=7|issue=203|format=PDF|publisher=HobbyPress|date=October 1990|page=32|lang=es}}</ref>

== Sequel ==
: ''See main article:'' ''[[P-47 Aces]]''
In 1995, an arcade-only sequel titled ''P-47 Aces'' was developed by NMK and published by Jaleco for the [[Mega System 32]] hardware. The sequel has the same concept but has some differences in gameplay such as players having the option to select four different airplanes with their own unique abilities. In Japan, it proved to be a popular arcade game.

